Ogun state government on Monday assured that it is ready to maximising the advantages of the overflow from Lagos state to better the standard of living of her citizens and residents in the areas of providing quality education, quality healthcare, transportation, clean water as well as clean electricity generation. The state governor, Prince Dapo Abiodun, who gave the assurance while featuring in an interview on a British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) Radio programme, Focus on Africa, emphatically stated that his state had laid a plan of actions and mechanisms that would ensure that Ogun absorbs all the shocks which its proximity to Lagos state could brings. While applauding the decision of the United Kingdom government to identify the state as one of the beneficiaries of the US$8 million fund under the aegis of its Global Future Cities Prosperity Fund Programme, Abiodun further assured that as people begin to migrate from Lagos to Ogun, to either live, work or play, the state is ready to give them quality of lives that is obtainable anywhere in the world. The Governor said the inclusion of Ogun state in the scheme “is a testimony to the fact that the state is not just a Gateway state to Nigeria, but that leadership of the state is poised to brace up to the challenges and turn all the push factors of the continent’s fifth largest economy to pull factors that can stand the test of millennial development”. “The Global Future Cities Prosperity Fund Programme recently identified Ogun state as one of the nineteen cities in ten countries that would benefit from the prosperity fund set up by the UK government. The governor stated that the present administration in the state would give the state a facelift that would attract the kind of investment capable of turning the state into a city that would could withstand modern development in terms of architecture and infrastructure. He disclosed that the state has also put in place an agency – Ogun Invest, which is the Ogun State Investment Promotion Agency – that would be saddled with the responsibility of doing everything that needs to be done to encourage the private sector do business with the state with relative ease. 